docs.abstract: On Juneteenth, a holiday that honors the end of slavery in America, the vice president said that “all lives matter’’ but twice declined to say that black lives matter.
docs.snippet: On Juneteenth, a holiday that honors the end of slavery in America, the vice president said that “all lives matter’’ but twice declined to say that black lives matter.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Vice President Mike Pence twice refused to say that “black lives matter” during an interview on a Philadelphia television station on Friday, insisting instead that “all lives matter in a very real sense.”

headline.main: Pence Won’t Say the Words ‘Black Lives Matter’ in an Interview
headline.print_headline: Pence Won’t Say ‘Black Lives Matter’ in a Juneteenth Interview

docs.abstract: We can’t tinker around the edges. We need to dismantle systems.
docs.snippet: We can’t tinker around the edges. We need to dismantle systems.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since the casual killing of George Floyd on camera, unprecedented protests — not policy papers — have radically shifted public opinion in support of the battle against systemic racism. The new nation being born in our streets may yet blossom into Langston Hughes’s “land that never has been yet / and yet must be” — but only if this movement refuses to let its truths be marched into the narrow cul-de-sac of “police reform.”

headline.main: What the Courage to Change History Looks Like

byline.original: By William Barber II, Liz Theoharis, Timothy B. Tyson and Cornel West

docs.abstract: Nuisance abatement laws force stores in low-income neighborhoods to operate almost as an arm of law enforcement.
docs.snippet: Nuisance abatement laws force stores in low-income neighborhoods to operate almost as an arm of law enforcement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ever since George Floyd was killed by Minneapolis police officers on May 25 after a grocery store reported that he had used a counterfeit $20 there, Muslim Americans have been asking why the store’s workers called the cops in the first place.

headline.main: Why Did Cup Foods Call the Cops on George Floyd?

docs.abstract: The competition’s organizers were told that players in England wanted to demonstrate their backing for the anti-racism movement when games resume next week.
docs.snippet: The competition’s organizers were told that players in England wanted to demonstrate their backing for the anti-racism movement when games resume next week.
docs.lead_paragraph: LEEDS, England — The captains of England’s leading soccer clubs have informed the Premier League that players intend to demonstrate their support for the Black Lives Matter movement when the competition resumes play next week.

headline.main: Premier League Captains Plan Show of Support for Black Lives Matter
headline.print_headline: Top Players  In England  Plan Tribute  To Protests

docs.abstract: Peter Fratus sent the emails to Commissioner Danielle Outlaw, who is African-American, amid some of the largest protests over the death of George Floyd, a criminal complaint said.
docs.snippet: Peter Fratus sent the emails to Commissioner Danielle Outlaw, who is African-American, amid some of the largest protests over the death of George Floyd, a criminal complaint said.
docs.lead_paragraph: A Massachusetts man has been charged with sending emails that contained threats of violence and racial slurs to Danielle Outlaw, the police commissioner in Philadelphia, during the city’s protests over the death of George Floyd, the authorities said on Tuesday.

headline.main: Man Charged With Sending Racist Threats to Philadelphia Police Leader

docs.abstract: The state became one of the first to make major changes in police practices in the wake of George Floyd’s killing, which has spurred nationwide protests.
docs.snippet: The state became one of the first to make major changes in police practices in the wake of George Floyd’s killing, which has spurred nationwide protests.
docs.lead_paragraph: New York on Friday became one of the first states to take meaningful action to restrict police forces after the killing of George Floyd, banning the use of chokeholds by law enforcement and repealing a half-century-old law that has kept police disciplinary records secret in the state.

headline.main: N.Y. Bans Chokeholds and Approves Other Measures to Restrict Police
headline.print_headline: New York State Moves to Check Police Conduct

byline.original: By Luis Ferré-Sadurní and Jesse McKinley

docs.abstract: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.snippet: The pianist and “Late Show” bandleader has been bringing musical wake-up calls to events across New York.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jon Batiste, the jazz pianist and “The Late Show With Stephen Colbert” bandleader, has spent the last three weekends marching in the streets of New York, leading musicians and protesters through hymns and songs like “We Shall Overcome” and “Down by the Riverside.” Those without a horn or drum sing and, at Mr. Batiste’s exhortation, say their names: George Floyd. Breonna Taylor. And many others.

headline.main: Jazz Is Built for Protests. Jon Batiste Is Taking It to the Streets.
headline.print_headline: Jon Batiste  Is Taking It To the Streets

docs.abstract: The Supreme Court developed the doctrine that serves as a shield for officers. A half-century later, it is at the center of the debate over policing.
docs.snippet: The Supreme Court developed the doctrine that serves as a shield for officers. A half-century later, it is at the center of the debate over policing.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Long before the death of George Floyd set off a nationwide uproar over police brutality, before protests erupted in 2014 over the death of Michael Brown in Ferguson, Mo., a 50-year-old man named Wayne Jones took a night stroll through the streets of Martinsburg, W.Va.

headline.main: Qualified Immunity Protection for Police Emerges as Flash Point Amid Protests
headline.print_headline: Legal Protection for Police Is Newly Scrutinized

docs.abstract: George Floyd’s death and the pandemic both reveal American infections. Why is the federal government undermining my fight against them?
docs.snippet: George Floyd’s death and the pandemic both reveal American infections. Why is the federal government undermining my fight against them?
docs.lead_paragraph: For a moment, the death of George Floyd has eclipsed the nation’s battle with a lethal virus. But the stories are not at odds. Both reveal an infection we have yet to overcome.

headline.main: Gretchen Whitmer: The Coronavirus Is a Civil Rights Battle, Too
headline.print_headline: We Need  A Vaccine For Racism

docs.abstract: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County walked with demonstrators protesting police brutality and the death of George Floyd.
docs.snippet: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County walked with demonstrators protesting police brutality and the death of George Floyd.
docs.lead_paragraph: Sheriff Christopher R. Swanson of Genesee County in Michigan stood before a crowd of protesters on Saturday. They were outraged over the death last week of George Floyd in Minneapolis, police brutality and systemic racism.

headline.main: Michigan Sheriff Took Off His Helmet and Marched With Protesters
